nnmaps <- read.csv("chicago-nmmaps.csv")
get_temp<-function(targetmonth,targetyear,data,celsius=FALSE,average_fn=mean){
  targetmonth=ifelse(is.numeric(targetmonth),targetmonth,substring(targetmonth,1,3))#filter the month into a short noted way
  if (!is.numeric(targetmonth)&!targetmonth%in%unique(data$month)){stop("Month out of Range")} #instead of write a list of month we use the month list in dataset
  if (is.numeric(targetmonth)&(targetmonth>12|targetmonth<1)){stop("Month out of Range")}
  if (targetyear>max(data$year)|targetyear<min(data$year)){stop("Year out of range")}
    t<-data%>%
      filter(year==targetyear,(month_numeric==targetmonth|month==targetmonth))%>%
      select(temp)
   return(ifelse(celsius,(average_fn(t$temp)-32)*5/9,average_fn(t$temp)))
}
get_temp("Apr", 1999, data = nnmaps)

df<-read.csv("df_for_ml_improved_new_market.csv")
a
#boxplot
df%>%ggplot()+geom_boxplot(aes(x=factor(year),y= price_usd))+labs(title="boxplot of price in usd of each year",x = "Year",
       y = "Price in USD")#need to change the years to factor for box
#scatter of mean
df%>%group_by(year)%>%summarise(mean_price=mean(price_usd))%>%
  ggplot()+geom_line(aes(x=year,y= mean_price))+labs(title="plot of the mean of price in usd of each year",x = "Year",
       y = "mean of Price in USD")

We can see that the mean of price in usd does not have a significant increase over years, while the extreme high outliers increase over time.

b
#code inspired from chatgpt
df_new <- df %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("Genre___"),
    names_to = "Genre",
    values_to = "Value"
  ) %>%
  filter(Value == 1) %>%
  mutate(Genre = str_remove(Genre, "Genre___")) %>% #delete the heading of the string
  select(-Value)

Because we observe that there may be multi-genre of an artwork, we set a new data set to record the results.

df_new%>%group_by(year,Genre)%>%summarise(count=n())%>%
  ggplot()+geom_line(aes(x=year,y=count,color=Genre),alpha=0.4)+labs(title = "count change over years")
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.

We can see that the count of painting, print, and other arts continue to grow slowly over time, while photography and sculpture have a similar, fast growth.

df_new%>%group_by(year)%>%summarise(count=n())%>%
  right_join(df_new,by=("year"="year"))%>%group_by(year,Genre)%>%summarise(proportion=n()/mean(count))%>%#the count are all same in one year, we just need one 
  ggplot()+geom_line(aes(x=year,y=proportion,color=Genre),alpha=0.4)+labs(title = "propotion change over years")
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.

We can see that the proportion of painting and other arts continue to drop over time, while photography and sculpture have fast growth. In the meantime, the proportion of print has a slow growth over time.

df_new%>%group_by(year,Genre)%>%
  summarise(total_sale=sum(price_usd))%>%#use the sum of price to represent the sale
  ggplot()+geom_line(aes(x=year,y=total_sale,color=Genre),alpha=0.4)+labs(title="plot of sale on different genreover year")
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.

We can see that the growth of photography in sale is the fastest, while the growth of sculpture is the second. The other three has a similar pattern of slow growth.
